# Checkout Kata
I deliberately kept things simple and avoided adding extra layers like repositories or services and even no .sln file.

For a problem this small, that would just add noise without much benefit.

## Overview

This is a simple checkout system that calculates the total price of a basket of items using SKU-based pricing.

It supports:
- Scanning items in any order
- Basic unit pricing per SKU
- Multi-buy offers (e.g. 3 for 130)
- Pricing rules that can be passed in when the checkout is created
- Basic validation for invalid input

The main goal of this solution was to keep things simple, readable, and built step-by-step using tests.

---

## Pricing Rules Example

| SKU | Unit Price | Special Offer |
|-----|------------|---------------|
| A   | 50         | 3 for 130     |
| B   | 30         | 2 for 45      |
| C   | 20         | None          |
| D   | 15         | None          |

---

## Approach

I built this using **TDD (Test Driven Development)**, starting with the simplest case and gradually adding more behaviour.

The order went roughly like this:
- Empty basket
- Single item pricing
- Multiple items
- Handling duplicates
- Adding multi-buy offers
- Mixed baskets with different rules

Each step was driven by tests, then refactored once it worked.

---

## Design decisions

I tried to keep the design as simple as possible.

- `Checkout` handles scanning items and calculating the total
- `PricingRule` holds the price for each SKU and any special offer
- Pricing rules are passed into the checkout so the pricing can change without touching the checkout logic
- Items are grouped by SKU when calculating the total to make applying offers easier

### Why grouping?

Grouping items by SKU made the offer logic much easier to reason about. Instead of dealing with items one by one, we can just look at quantities per SKU.

---

## Error handling

I added some basic validation to keep things safe:

- Scanning a null or empty item throws an exception
- Scanning an unknown SKU throws an exception

This is mainly to fail fast and avoid calculating with invalid data.


---

## Running tests

```bash
cd ./Kata.Tests

dotnet test